00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil

4
00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.000
And I'm Piffer. In this program we're talking about happiness

5
00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:17.000
So what makes you happy Neil?

6
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Oh, it makes me happy when I'm with a group of old friends and we're having a good laugh

7
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.000
How about you Piffer?

8
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Cats make me very happy, especially if I see a cat

9
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
on the street that I don't know and it lets me give it a little stroke

10
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.000
That always makes me happy.

11
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.000
I'm not surprised, that sounds great

12
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
So happiness means different things to different people

13
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
But what's for sure is that most people would like to be happy

14
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:50.000
And the small Himalayan kingdom of Bhutan has taken this to a new level

15
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
With the idea of gross national happiness or gnH

16
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
We'll be hearing more about gross national happiness

17
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
And learning some useful new vocabulary soon

18
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:03.000
But first Piffer I have a question for you

19
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
Of course, it's not just the people of Bhutan who want to be happy

20
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:12.000
In fact, the United Nations has even announced an international day of happiness

21
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.000
But when is that?

22
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Is international happiness day a, the 20th of March, b, the 20th of June

23
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Or c, the 20th of November

24
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
I'm going to say the 20th of June

25
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Because it would be sunny in the UK

26
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Okay, let's find out if you're right at the end of the programme

27
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Now briefly, gross national happiness means

28
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Preserving Bhutan's natural environment and culture

29
00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:41.000
Through sustainable and eco-friendly development

30
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Bhutan's government sees these goals

31
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
As more important than growing the economy at any cost

32
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
For many years Bhutan was closed to the outside world

33
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
The first foreign tourists arrived in 1974

34
00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.000
And television was only introduced in 1999

35
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
The King of Bhutan wanted to modernise the country

36
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And give it the benefits of modern technology

37
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
But without damaging traditional culture

38
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:14.000
So he invited outside experts to develop the idea of gross national happiness

39
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:19.000
One expert was Dr. Harvin Toe, speaking here to Charmaine Kozia

40
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Presenter of BBC World Service programme, The Inquiry

41
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:28.000
So his idea was how could we modernise an open-our country

42
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
Without losing its culture, its environment

43
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
And its very strong social fabric

44
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
Because Bhutan was one of the only countries in Asia

45
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
who was never colonised therefore its culture is very intact and vibrant

46
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Mainly Buddhist culture

47
00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.000
And so the idea was that gross national happiness

48
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Should be the focus on all government decisions and policies

49
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:57.000
So the well-being and happiness of citizens took them to stage

50
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Bhutan has a strong social fabric

51
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Meaning there are good relationships within communities

52
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.000
And these holds society together

53
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Unlike other Asian countries Bhutan was never colonised

54
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
So its Buddhist culture and traditions are intact

55
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
They're complete and unspoiled

56
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
As a result the happiness of Bhutan's people took centre stage

57
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
It became the most important thing

58
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Bhutan's emphasis on happiness has been admired around the world

59
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:27.000
But there have been problems too

60
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
One is the migration of Bhutanese workers to India and other countries

61
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
In search of better paid jobs and opportunities

62
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Something known as the Brain Drain

63
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.000
So in 2023 the King of Bhutan announced a multi-million-dollar project

64
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Called The Mindfulness City

65
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:50.000
A new Himalayan city built on spiritual and environmental principles

66
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
All powered by renewable energy

67
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Originally from Bhutan, Dr. Lowang Ugyel is the project's director

68
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:02.000
And spoke with Charming Kozia for the BBC World Services, The Inquiry

69
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
The project is also about reversing Bhutan's brain drain

70
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.000
The intention is to have locals run this whole mindfulness city

71
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:16.000
So in that sense it's also to attract the migrants that have left

72
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
And in the process of having worked abroad

73
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Again the extra skills come back to the mental and the city and work

74
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
As well as being a futuristic e-co-city

75
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
The Mindfulness City hopes to stop Bhutan's brain drain

76
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
By attracting workers back home to Bhutan

77
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.000
These local workers can then use the extra skills that they've learned abroad

78
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Through up-skilling and up-skilling is the process where workers skills are improved

79
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Through training

80
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
The idea of gross national happiness might sound unusual

81
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:53.000
But it's interesting to see Bhutan balancing economic growth with the happiness of its people

82
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Yes, that's true and it reminds me of your question now

83
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Yes, I asked you what the date of international happiness day is

84
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.000
I said it was the 20th of June and the summer in the UK

85
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Well maybe it's better for people in the Southern Hemisphere

86
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Because it's actually the 20th of March

87
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Ah nice

